: true, "mention": "ICAM", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8611556887626648, "span": {"begin": 2624, "end": 2628}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7412"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "VCAM", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9790904521942139, "span": {"begin": 2633, "end": 2637}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003681"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Oxidative stress", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9048939943313599, "span": {"begin": 2716, "end": 2732}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3949"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "low-density lipoproteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9975900650024414, "span": {"begin": 2765, "end": 2789}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "macrophages", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8647376298904419, "span": {"begin": 2835, "end": 2846}}, {"id": ["mim:108725", "mesh:D050197"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atherosclerotic", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9989472031593323, "span": {"begin": 2872, "end": 2887}}, {"id": ["mesh:D058226"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "plaque", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8988480567932129, "span": {"begin": 2897, "end": 2903}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lipid cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9067233800888062, "span": {"begin": 2955, "end": 2966}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7040"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TGF-&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.997756838798523, "span": {"begin": 3028, "end": 3038}}], "text": "The biological plausibility of the linkage between oxidative stress and pro-inflammatory mediators is strongly supported by review papers on the subject (Ping et al., 2020; Ramadan et al., 2021; Slezak et al., 2017; Slezak et al., 2015; Sylvester et al., 2018; Venkatesulu et al., 2018; Wang et al., 2019a). Pro-inflammatory mediators are released in instances of cell damage to recruit macrophages, monocytes, and other scavengers to ingest and degrade dead and damaged cells. As a major pathway of cell damage, oxidative stress causes upregulation of pro-inflammatory mediators including NF-&kappa;B, transforming growth factor-&beta; (TGF-&beta;), tumour necrosis factor-&alpha; (TNF-&alpha;), interleukin-1 (IL-1), and interleukin-6 (IL-6) (Ping et al., 2020; Slezak et al., 2017; Slezak et al., 2015; Sylvester et al., 2018; Venkatesulu et al., 2018; Wang et al., 2019a). Oxidative stress also stimulates a rise in pro-inflammatory adhesion factors, such as E-selectin, intercellular adhesion molecule-1 (ICAM1), and vascular cell adhesion molecule-1 (VCAM1), which facilitate inflammation by assisting the entrance of inflammatory cells into tissues and recruiting macrophages (Ping et al., 2020; Slezak et al., 2017; Slezak et al., 2015; Sylvester et al., 2018; Venkatesulu et al., 2018; Wang et al., 2019a).&nbsp;  &nbsp;  Once antioxidant levels become exhausted in a state of oxidative stress, ROS are present in higher concentrations and can therefore act more effectively as second messenger signalling molecules in activating pro-inflammatory transcription factors, such as NF-&kappa;B, and stimulating production of pro-inflammatory cytokines, such as IL-1, IL-6 and TNF-&alpha; (Ping et al., 2020; Sylvester et al., 2018; Wang et al., 2019a). NF-&kappa;B is normally kept in an inactive state through formation of a complex with the IkB family of inhibitor proteins but is activated by oxidative stress through nuclear translocation of the complex to the promoter areas of inflammation regulatory genes (Ping et al., 2020; Slezak et al., 2017). The macrophages that are recruited in the resulting inflammatory response can also produce ROS and activate the pro-inflammatory mediator, TGF-&beta;, forming a positive feedback loop (Venkatesulu et al., 2018). Another positive feedback loop is formed by ROS and NF-&kappa;B, as ROS activates NF-&kappa;B, resulting in the expression of the genes cyclooxygenase-2 (COX-2) and 5-lipoxygenase (5-LPO), which are responsible for ROS production (Ping et al., 2020). In addition, NF-&kappa;B is also involved in the production of the pro-inflammatory adhesion factors ICAM and VCAM (Ping et al., 2020; Slezak et al., 2017; Slezak et al., 2015).&nbsp;  &nbsp;  Oxidative stress may also result in oxidation of low-density lipoproteins, allowing the lipoproteins to be ingested by macrophages. This could initiate the atherosclerotic process (plaque build-up in the arteries) and subsequently lead to lipid cells secreting pro-inflammatory cytokines, such as IL-1&beta; and TGF-&beta; (Ramadan et al., 2021; Slezak et al., 2017; Sylvester et al., 2018; Ping et al., 2020; Venkatesulu et al., 2018).&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:53:16 +0000 2026"}